- Annual profits are reported in millions of dollars;
- The profit value of 9862 million dollars is a specific threshold used to filter companies;
- The sector hierarchy is built to understand the organizational structure of sectors.

- "Average revenue" is the mean annual revenue of companies within a sector, calculated by summing the revenues and dividing by the number of companies;
- "Average market capitalization" is the mean market capitalization of companies within a sector, calculated by summing the market capitalizations and dividing by the number of companies;
- "Sector description" provides a brief overview of the activities and characteristics of the companies within each sector.

- "titans of industry" refers to companies with significant financial metrics;
- "their sectors" and "the areas they dominate" refer to the sector and industry in which the companies operate;
- "vast sum of $100,000 million" and "towers over $50 billion" are metaphorical expressions for the revenue and market capitalization thresholds, respectively.

- The "top 10 companies" refers to the companies ranked 1 to 10 in the Fortune 500 list;
- "Revenue differences" are calculated by subtracting the financial revenue from the reported revenue for each company;
- The Fortune 500 list is an annual ranking of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.

- "Sector" refers to a broad category of companies grouped by their primary business activities;
- "Industry" is a more specific subset within a sector, grouping companies with similar business activities;
- "Profit ratio" is the percentage of the industry's profits relative to the sector's total profits.
